General View--Lower Manhattan, Financial District: Shown are three views of the city's financial area. View 1 is toward the East River from Whitehall Building and shows prominently the Standard Oil and the International Telephone (flag) Buildings. In the foreground is the old tower of the Produce Exchange. Brooklyn is in the background.

View 2 is southwestward across Battery Park and the Acquarium. The Standard Oil Building is on the right and on the left is the City Bank Farmers Trust Building.

View 3 is westward and shows the West Street Building at Albany Street, one of the earliest skyscrapers.

P. L. Sperr

View 1: 1929
View 3: 1933

text:
(1) West Street, east side, from Albany to Carlisle Streets. Also shown is Albany Street, south side, east from West, to and including Greenwich Streets. August 15, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

(2) The same, at a later date, showing the area after practically all the houses which formerly stood there were razed. Albany Street is seen on the left. April 17, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

(3) The same, from a different angle. Note the 5-story house at the N.E. corner of Carlisle Street in process of being demolished. Also shown (background) is the Singer Building, at the N.W. corner of Broadway and Liberty Street. April 17, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.
